\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf0  v1 \
OAS3\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b0\fs24 \cf0 \strokec2 This API version only applies to sites using Nova Grid Edge Management Units.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \strokec2 The Koios API strives to provide utility operators the same level of programmatic control over their SparkMeter Nova assets that they enjoy through the Koios web UI.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 Authentication\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b0\fs24 \cf0 As with the data API, all client requests must be include the 
\f3\fs26 \strokec2 X-API-KEY
\f2\fs24 \strokec2  and 
\f3\fs26 \strokec2 X-API-SECRET
\f2\fs24 \strokec2  headers.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 Authorization\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b0\fs24 \cf0 Koios introduces the concept of granular API tokens. With this, API tokens may be granted access to a subset of resource types in the system, with monitoring or full access. If a request is made using a valid token, but the action is not permitted based on the permission grants of the token, it will error with a 
\f3\fs26 \strokec2 ForbiddenError
\f2\fs24 \strokec2 .\
For the pilot, there is no affordance for granular permissions. One may create "Monitoring" or "Full access" API tokens.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa298\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs36 \cf0 Requests\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b0\fs24 \cf0 Requests follow industry best practices:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0\cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Resource paths are RESTful.\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0
\f3\fs26 \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 GET
\f2\fs24  requests are idempotent.\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f3\fs26 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 PATCH
\f2\fs24  operations observe a subset of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://jsonpatch.com/"}}{\fldrslt \cf3 \ul \ulc3 \strokec3 JSON-Patch}} standard (with JSON pointers being limited to the root resource). This restriction may be lifted in the future.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 \strokec2 Pagination\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f2\b0\fs24 \cf0 \strokec2 All endpoints that retrieve resource collections are paginated. 
\f3\fs26 \strokec2 GET
\f2\fs24 \strokec2  requests will default to the first page of results. The response will include a 
\f3\fs26 \strokec2 cursor
\f2\fs24 \strokec2  property. The next page of the request can be fetched by passing the property value in the request path (e.g., 
\f3\fs26 \strokec2 GET /v1/sites?cursor=<cursor>
\f2\fs24 \strokec2 ). Unlike with the data API, this cursor does not expire.\
By default, all pages will be restricted to 50 records. This may be adjusted by providing a value for the optional 
\f3\fs26 \strokec2 per_page
\f2\fs24 \strokec2  query parameter. If too many records are requested, the request will return with a 
\f3\fs26 \strokec2 400 Bad Request
\f2\fs24 \strokec2  error response, with an informative payload.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
